The fluorescence quenching efficiency of the crude N-CDs decreased when tartrazine concentrations increased from 0 to 195 μM (Fig. 6
                        a), and Hg2+ concentrations increased from 0 to 55 μM (Fig. 6d). It was linear with tartrazine concentrations within 5–70 μM (R2 = 0.99299) and 95–195 μM (R2 = 0.99064) with the low detection limits (LOD) 353.77 nM (Fig. 6b); while that of the purified N-CDs was linear with tartrazine concentrations from 0.25 to 5 μM, (R2 = 0.993777) and 5–50 μM (R2 = 0.9817) with LOD 34.98 nM (Fig. 6c) (Table 1
                        ) [31–37]. The fluorescence quenching efficiency of the crude N-CDs was linear with Hg2+ concentrations within 0–20 μM (R2 = 0.99766) and 20–55 μM (R2 = 0.99338) with LOD 152.28 nM (Fig. 6e); while that of the purified N-CDs was linear with Hg2+ concentrations from 0.25 to 5 μM (R2 = 0.9988) and 10–50 μM (R2 = 0.9996) with LOD 29.64 nM (Fig. 6f) (Table 2
                        ) [38–47].
